    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"481963\">David Loeffler</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Zp.20is.20compact.3F/near/467750934\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Tagging <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"250372\">Ashvni Narayanan</span> since this must have come up in her PhD thesis.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hello! Sorry I'm just seeing this. If the question is regarding Z_p is compact, I did prove this in Lean 3. In particular, I had shown that Z_p is profinite. All the code is <a href=\"https://github.com/laughinggas/p-adic-L-functions\">here</a> .  I managed to partly port some of the code to Lean4, which is <a href=\"https://github.com/laughinggas/padic-L-functions4/tree/master/PadicLFunctions4\">here</a>. </p>\n<p>If you are looking for results regarding <code>Z_p</code>, <code>ZMod</code> or Bernoulli numbers, there is a high chance it exists in these repos. Happy to assist further in any way I can! :)</p>",
